{"cards":[{"lines":[{"type":"title","text":"Sound waves"},{"type":"headline","text":"Travel in three dimensions"},{"type":"headline","text":"Wave front is expanding sphere"}]},{"lines":[{"type":"title","text":"Sound intensity"},{"type":"headline","text":"Power of sound per unit area"},{"type":"headline","text":"Diminishes proportionally to square of distance from source"}]}],"definitions":[],"secText":["  <b>Essential Question: <\/b>  <b>    <br \/>  <\/b>How are sound levels measured?","  <b>Enduring Understandings:<\/b>  <b>    <br \/>  <\/b>1. <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='14' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='0'>Sound waves<\/a> expand and travel in three dimensions. Sound waves can be modeled as an expanding sphere. <br \/>2. <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='14' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='2' data-subsection='0'>Sound intensity<\/a> can be calculated by dividing the power of a sound by the area in which it expands.<br \/>3. <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='14' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='3' data-subsection='0'>Sound levels<\/a> are measured in decibels and are a ratio of sound intensities.","  <b>Vocabulary:<\/b>  <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='14' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='0'>wave front<\/a>","  <b>STEM Skills:<\/b>  <b>    <br \/>  <\/b>1. Review ratios."],"objNames":["wb_spherical_concept","wb_sound_intensity_concepts"]}